    ""***An Unexpected Encounter***""
    # (blank line)
    ""Late afternoon sun slanted through the trees as Daniel and BailieBoy parted company with Kevin, heading back towards the car. Their path took them through Centennial Park, a stretch of green that followed the creek. BailieBoy, ever curious, suddenly darted away, disappearing into a thicket of bushes near an old cottonwood tree.""
    # (blank line)
    "... Bailie,\" Daniel called, \"let's go."
    # (blank line)
    ""A soft giggle, musical and unexpected, was the only reply. Daniel pushed through the leaves and stopped. A young woman was sitting in the shade, her back against the tree. She looked like a college student, petite and barely 5 foot 2, with wide, curious eyes. One leg of her hiking pants was rolled up, revealing a nasty scrape on her shin. In her hands was a small, sleek, metallic object—a medpack of some kind—that was emitting a soft blue light as she pressed it against the wound. BailieBoy was happily licking her face, his tail thumping a steady rhythm against the ground. He seemed captivated by her, nuzzling against her arm. And then he smelled it. The smell. The mysterious, alien scent from the mountains. It was her. And something in her backpack. Something small, and warm, and purring. A kitten. But the other smell, the cold, clean smell of ozone and lightning... that was all her.""
    # (blank line)
    ""She looked up at Daniel, her smile shy. "He's friendly," she said.""
    # (blank line)
    """Too friendly, sometimes," Daniel replied, smiling back. "Sorry if he bothered you." He noticed a faint, pleasant aroma, like cinnamon and warm earth.""
    # (blank line)
    """Not at all. He's a good boy." She giggled again as BailieBoy gave her another enthusiastic lick.""
    # (blank line)
    ""This was FoF, or FithOfFive, a student anthropologist from a civilization nestled deep within the galaxy's core. Her culture was a loosely knit libertarian society dominated by large, sprawling families who provided their children with advanced technology and education, allowing for independent lives from a very early age. Her base of operations was a small, concealed shuttle hidden in a remote valley of the Rocky Mountains near Pikes Peak, which in turn was serviced by a much larger star cruiser cloaked in a geosynchronous orbit high above. Her thesis was on the curious, chaotic species that called themselves humans. Her natural form, something akin to a Terran sloth, was hardly suited for fieldwork, so she employed advanced genomic tech to weave herself a temporary human body—this small, unassuming form that allowed her to walk among her subjects unnoticed. The fall had been clumsy, a miscalculation on a rocky trail, but the injury was minor. A tiny implant behind her ear chimed with a silent, internal voice, *'Minor tissue damage detected. Recommend bio-stasis and cellular regeneration.'* The medpack was already responding, a thought-activated device linked to the network of near-invisible implants in each of her joints. These implants, communicating with each other via a constant, whisper-quiet stream of neutrinos, formed her personal command interface, a silent chorus of data and diagnostics that fed directly into her consciousness. BailieBoy's sudden, affectionate appearance was a delightful, un-anticiapted data point.""
    # (blank line)
    ""FoF had studied recent human history and was well aware of the lesser advanced galactic civilizations that had sent their own probes into the solar system. She was particularly interested in the events of 2025, and the frantic, often contradictory, reports surrounding the object designated 3i/ATLAS.""
