    ""*A mental excerpt from FoF’s private logs, cross-referencing her thesis research with Consensus intelligence briefings.*""
    # (blank line)
    ""**The Vraxx (Designation: Dangerous)**""
    ""The Consensus has had limited, and uniformly negative, interactions with the Vraxx. Originating from a high-gravity world in the Kepler-186 system, they are a species of relentless expansionists. Their technology, while impressive by human standards, is considered brutish and unsophisticated by the Consensus. It is powerful but lacks elegance, much like their diplomacy. `3i/ATLAS` is a perfect example of their methodology: a loud, unsubtle military scout designed to assess resource value and planetary defenses. Their goal is not communion, but consumption. They see other civilizations as either obstacles or opportunities for strip-mining. They are predictable, which makes them manageable, but their aggression makes them a constant, low-level threat to emerging civilizations like Earth's.""
    # (blank line)
    ""**The Cygnans (Designation: Friendly)**""
    ""Hailing from the accretion disk of the Cygnus X-1 black hole, the Cygnans are not biological in any sense that a human would understand. They are beings of pure energy, living within the complex magnetic fields of their home. They are galactic nomads and archivists, their 'ships' being focused gravitational waves that carry their consciousness across the void. They have visited the Sol system several times over the past millennia, their passing noted by humans as unexplained gravitational anomalies or bursts of high-energy particles. Their interest is purely academic. They collect data, observe, and move on. They are considered friendly because their core directive is preservation of knowledge, and they will not interfere. Communication with them is nearly impossible, as it requires a deep understanding of quantum physics and modulated Hawking radiation.""
    # (blank line)
    ""**The Klepht (Designation: Dangerous)**""
    ""The Klepht are the locusts of the galaxy. A parasitic, insectoid species, they travel in massive, self-sustaining swarms, moving from star system to star system. They are the ultimate consumers. Their technology is entirely based on self-replication and biomass conversion. They land on a planet, and within a few standard years, they have consumed everything—the atmosphere, the oceans, the very crust of the planet itself—and converted it into new ships and new generations of Klepht. They leave behind only a dead, silent husk. The Consensus has designated them a top-tier existential threat. Their swarms have been responsible for the extinction of at least three known sentient species. The only good thing about the Klepht is that their swarms are detectable from a great distance, their energy consumption a screaming beacon in the void. So far, they have shown no interest in the Sol system.""
    # (blank line)
    ""**The Sentinel (Designation: Unknown/Danger-Extreme)**""
    ""The Sentinel, or Sentinels, are a complete enigma. The name is a Consensus designation for the source of the gravitational anomalies around Jupiter. Their technology is so far beyond our own that it appears to be magic. The ability to use a black hole's singularity as a transportation hub is a theoretical concept that our best minds have not been able to solve for millennia. We do not know who they are, where they come from (other than the connection to the Magellanic Clouds), or what they want. They could be observers, like us, but on a scale we can't comprehend. Or they could be something else entirely. The Watcher AI has logged their presence for centuries, but there has never been any direct contact, no communication. They are a silent, god-like presence. The silence is what makes them so terrifying. An unknown variable of this magnitude must be considered a danger of the highest possible order. Their non-interference could be a matter of policy, or it could be the simple indifference of a giant to the ants at its feet.""
