    # (blank line)
    ""Later that night, you call Jay. You frame it as a hypothetical, a security problem you’re wrestling with. You tell him about a friend of a friend, a brilliant artist trapped by a predatory data-loan. You ask him, theoretically, how one might go about erasing such a debt.""
    # (blank line)
    ""Jay listens patiently, his face a mask of professional calm. When you’re finished, he’s silent for a long moment. Then he says, “You’re being played, Danny.”""
    # (blank line)
    ""“What are you talking about? It’s a hypothetical.”""
    # (blank line)
    ""“It’s never a hypothetical. It’s a test. A loyalty test. A recruitment test. You’re being groomed. They flatter you, they give you a noble cause, they make you feel like a hero. And then they own you. I’ve seen it a hundred times. It’s the oldest trick in the book.”""
    # (blank line)
    ""“You’re paranoid, Jay.”""
    # (blank line)
    ""“I’m a cybersecurity professional. Paranoia is my job description. Look, I don’t know who this woman is, but she’s not who she says she is. And if you do this, if you cross that line, there’s no coming back. You’ll be a criminal. A tool. And they will use you until you’re all used up, and then they will discard you. Don’t do it, Danny. Don’t be a fool.”""
    # (blank line)
    ""The call ends, and you’re left with a cold knot of fear in your stomach. Jay’s words are a bucket of ice water on the fire of your idealism. But Zorya’s face, her pleading eyes, her belief in you… they’re a powerful drug. And you’re already addicted.""
    # (blank line)
    ""FoF, observing Daniel's internal struggle through the drone, felt a familiar echo. The implants behind her ears picked up the subtle fluctuations in his vocal stress, while the network of sensors in her joints analyzed his posture, feeding a stream of biometric data into her consciousness. A quiet, analytical voice in her head, one of several her implants could generate on demand, murmured, *'Subject exhibits elevated heart rate, cortisol levels consistent with severe emotional distress.'* Her own childhood, though filled with advanced education, lacked emotional warmth. Her family, proponents of radical self-reliance, viewed emotional attachments as vulnerabilities. She remembered a time she'd found a injured bird and tried to nurse it back to health, only to be told by her eldest brother that "nature's course should not be interfered with." The bird died, and with it, a small part of her youthful empathy. Another internal voice, this one warmer, more philosophical, queried, *'Is this "healing" impulse a convergent evolutionary trait? Cross-referencing...'*. With a thought, she sent a query through the neutrino link to her orbiting starship, commanding it to search the galactic database for species that exhibited similar patterns of altruistic behavior triggered by emotional compromise. She wondered if Daniel, in his own way, was trying to heal something broken within himself by helping Kaito.""
    # (blank line)
