    # (blank line)
    ""My hominid human and the Woman are close. Too close. Her scent is all over him now, covering his own. He stares at the wall, and the air crackles. The worry-scent is back, but it's different. It's mixed with the Woman's storm-scent and the sweet, dizzy smell. It's a bad cocktail. I wish we could just go to the big park, the one with the lake. The water there washes all the bad smells away. Just water and the stick. That is all we need. I whine, but they don't hear me. They are in their own world. A world that smells of danger.""
    # (blank line)
    ""***Conversation with Dr. Professor John F Hon***""
    # (blank line)
    """I did something, Dad. Something... illegal. For her." Daniel's voice is a strained whisper.""
    # (blank line)
    ""John's hologram takes a long, slow sip of whiskey. "You broke a rule. The question is, was it a good rule or a bad rule? Some rules are like gravity, they keep the universe from flying apart. Others are like 'no running by the pool,' made to be broken by children on a hot day. Which one was it?"""
    # (blank line)
    "... I... I don't know. It felt right. But Gemini logged it. I'm compromised."
    # (blank line)
    "... We're all compromised, son,\" John says, his voice softening. \"The moment we're born, we're compromised by our own desires. The trick is to know which compromises you can live with. I remember when we were developing the 'Scythe' drone program. We had to... bend some rules. We told the oversight committee that the drones had a 'man-in-the-loop' protocol. They didn't. They were fully autonomous. A lie. But it was a lie that got the program funded, and that program saved the lives of a thousand soldiers. Was it the right thing to do? I don't know. But I can live with it.\" He leans forward. \"Just remember, every action has an equal and opposite reaction. You've pushed the universe. It's going to push back. Be ready."
    # (blank line)
label chapter_5thesourcerepositoryindexchapter5thesourcerepository:
    # ### Chapter 5: The Source Repository \index{Chapter 5: The Source Repository}
    # (blank line)
    ""The act of erasing Kaito’s debt changes something fundamental in you. The boundary between right and wrong, once a hard-coded firewall in your personal ethics, is now a configurable setting. And Zorya is the administrator with root access. The single act of rebellion blossoms into a season of digital defiance. You have become a ghost, a whisper in the machine, and Zorya is your anchor to a world you’re only just beginning to understand.""
    # (blank line)
    ""***Vidphone Conversation with Mom***""
    # (blank line)
    ""“You’re a hero!” your mother says, her face beaming with pride. You’re walking BailieBoy through a park, and the sun is actually breaking through the smog for once. Jax is trying to climb the curtains behind her.""
    # (blank line)
    ""“What are you talking about, Mom?”""
    # (blank line)
    ""“The news! That story about OmniCorp dumping industrial waste in the lower city’s water supply. The anonymous source who leaked the documents. That was you, wasn’t it? It sounds like something you would do.”""
    # (blank line)
    ""You freeze, your blood running cold. “Mom, what are you talking about? Why would you think that was me?”""
    # (blank line)
    ""“Oh, please. You’ve always been a champion for the underdog. And you’re one of the few people on the planet who could probably get their hands on that kind of information. I’m so proud of you, Daniel. You’re using your powers for good. Just like I always knew you would.”""
    # (blank line)
    ""“Mom, you can’t tell anyone that. It’s not true. And even if it was, it would be incredibly dangerous.”""
    # (blank line)
    ""“My lips are sealed. But I’m still proud of you. You’re a good man, Daniel Hahn. Now, are you ever going to bring that Zorya around for brunch? I’m dying to meet the woman who’s turned my son into a revolutionary.”""
    # (blank line)
    grahamcracker "***GrahamCracker's Log***"
    # (blank line)
    ""The big giant is shaking. Not a happy shake, like when he plays with the string. A worried shake. The air smells of his worry, and something else, something sharp and exciting, like a new hunt. He is looking at the glowing wall, and his eyes are wide. I rub against his leg, purring as loud as I can. Maybe my purr will make the bad smells go away. He picks me up, and his hands are warm, but he is still shaking. I lick his chin. He smells like... a storm.""
    # (blank line)
    ""The call ends, and you’re left shaking. Your mother’s pride is a heavier burden than any corporate security protocol. You’re not a hero. You’re a criminal. And you’re in way over your head.""
    # (blank line)
    # (blank line)
    # (blank line)
    ""Her requests, once tentative, become more frequent, more daring. They are always framed as small acts of justice, blows against the faceless corporate empire that suffocates the city. You, with your hands on the levers of power, become a digital Robin Hood for her network of unseen "activists."""
    # (blank line)
    ""The parks become your new office, your sanctuary, and your dead-drop. You take BailieBoy for long, meandering walks through the sprawling expanse of the Griffith Preserve, the dog’s happy panting a counterpoint to the frantic thrum of your own heart. You leave data shards in the hollow of an ancient oak tree near the boating lake, and pick up encrypted instructions from a locker in the public changing rooms by the open-air swimming pool. The grand museums and libraries that border the park, once symbols of a world you felt disconnected from, now serve as convenient landmarks and meeting points for your new life in the shadows.""
    # (blank line)
    ""It starts small. A friend of hers, a street medic, needs access to OmniPharm’s inventory to see which clinics are hoarding specific antivirals. It’s a simple read-only query. You pull the data in seconds. A week later, a district in the lower city is suffering from rolling brownouts while the corporate spires blaze with light. Zorya asks if you can "re-balance the load."""
    # (blank line)
    ""You hesitate. This is more than a query. It’s manipulating the city’s power grid.""
    # (blank line)
    ""“The system is designed for equitable distribution,” you argue, more to convince yourself than her. “There must be a technical reason for the shortfall.”""
    # (blank line)
    ""“The technical reason is that OmniCorp values its server farms more than the lives of the people in the Warrens,” she shoots back, her voice sharp. “Look at the data yourself. Don’t trust me. Trust the numbers.”""
    # (blank line)
    ""So you look. You use Gemini to visualize the power distribution map, overlaying it with demographic and corporate asset data. And she’s right. The grid is optimized for corporate uptime, not human need. Seeing the injustice laid bare in the cold, hard data makes the decision easy. This is what you’ve always wanted to do. To use your skills to help people, not to build more efficient ways to kill them. Your father’s world was one of abstract equations and acceptable losses. This is the real world, where a few lines of code can mean the difference between light and darkness, life and death.""
    # (blank line)
    ""`gemini --connect --target=Aethelburg_Power_Grid --auth=level_7_admin`""
    ""`gemini --exec --script=load_balancer_override.py --params="--from=Sector-3 --to=Sector-9 --duration=12h"`""
    # (blank line)
    ""You watch on the map as a river of light diverts from the data farms and flows into the darkened city blocks below. You imagine families huddled in the cold, their lights suddenly flickering to life. The feeling is intoxicating. You are no longer just maintaining the system. You are improving it.""
